\subsection{Information retrieval tests}
To ensure the quality of the search results returned by our IR system themselves, we also perform a series of information retrieval tests. These tests measure the accuracy and completeness of the search results, which is naturally a major requirement for all three interviewed users. During the tests, a focus is set on measuring the recall of the system, which is crucial in this scenario, as missing even a single relevant patent can have serious consequences. For example, David has voiced the requirement to identify possible infringement issues using the search engine. For this, it must clearly be able to find \textit{all} relevant or similar patents, given a search term or patent. Also, if support for filing patents, a requirement of John, would be implemented on the platform, making sure the patent is unique would also be a major requirement. The focus on recall is explained in more detail later on.

We use an established dataset of patents for our tests, consisting of a wide range of patent documents with varying levels of complexity and technical detail. We measure the performance of the system using several metrics, including Precision-and-Recall, and nDCG (normalized discounted cumulative gain). Precision measures the proportion of retrieved results that are relevant to the user's query. It is calculated as the ratio of true positives (TP) to the sum of true positives and false positives (FP):
\begin{equation\*}
\text{Precision} = \frac{TP}{TP + FP}
\end{equation\*}
A high precision score indicates that the search engine is returning mostly relevant results, while a low precision score indicates that many of the results are irrelevant. Recall, on the other hand, measures the proportion of relevant results that are retrieved by the search engine. It is calculated as the ratio of true positives (TP) to the sum of true positives and false negatives (FN):
\begin{equation\*}
\text{Recall} = \frac{TP}{TP + FN}
\end{equation\*}
A high recall score indicates that the search engine is returning most or all of the relevant results, while a low recall score suggests that many relevant results are being missed. In the context of patent search it is especially important to optimize for recall, as it is critical to ensure that all relevant patents are returned in the search results. This makes recall a much more important metric in our case than in more general search engines. Still, precision is clearly also important for the ease-of-use of the system and should not be neglected completely.

The normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain (nDCG) is another metric commonly used in information retrieval. It takes into account both the overall relevance and the position of the retrieved item in the search results. It is defined as
$$nDCG\_k = \frac{DCG\_k}{IDCG\_k}$$
where $k$ is the rank position up to which the metric is calculated (e.g. the first page of results), $DCG\_k$ is the Discounted Cumulative Gain at rank $k$, and $IDCG\_k$ is the Ideal Discounted Cumulative Gain at rank $k$. The Discounted Cumulative Gain is calculated as
$$DCG\_k = rel\_1 + \sum\_{i=2}^k \frac{rel\_i}{\log\_2 i},$$
where $rel\_i$ is the relevance score of the $i$-th search result. The Ideal Discounted Cumulative Gain is the $DCG\_k$ of the search results in the ideal order. The nDCG is therefore a value between 0 and 1, where 1 is a perfect result. In our case, nDCG is important because it allows us to not only consider relevance, but also the rank position of retrieved patents. It for example provides a way to weigh more recent or popular patents more heavily, which is a way to fulfill all interviewed users requirement to stay up to date with industry trends.

In addition to testing the baseline version of our search engine, we also evaluate the performance of the different helper features and advanced search features tested in the Online Controlled Experiments to investigate their impact on the search results. Overall, the information retrieval tests help us to identify areas for improvement in the IR system and to point out way to fine-tune its performance to optimize the recall. It is important that the system returns all relevant patents, so it can provide the users with a comprehensive and accurate image of the patent situation given various search terms or conditions.

